  <section class="reading">
    <span class="section-label"><span class="num">01</span>/ what the graphs know</span>
    <h1>Methods</h1>
    <p>
      The questions on the <a href="/networks">company map</a> and the
      <a href="/funding">funding map</a> are answered by the twelve statistical analyses below,
      methods due mostly to the spectral network-statistics school. This page is the layer
      underneath the maps: each panel states its finding, shows the full evidence, explains the
      mechanism under "how it works", and carries the citations and the caveats in the fine
      print. Ask the questions on the maps; check the work here. Both graphs are drawn from
      public information only, and the fog of war is real: most partnerships, customer deals,
      and investor positions are never announced, and the quiet ones are missing
      systematically — a well-publicized company looks better connected than an equally
      connected quiet one. An absent edge is a fact about the map, never about the world.
      Each panel's fine print says which way its statistic bends under that bias; each
      question's evidence drawer carries the same line.
    </p>
  </section>
